50|$|In 1860, the Russian Government at the {{instance}} of Otto Sturves invited the Governments of Belgium, France, Prussia and England to connect their triangulations {{in order to}} measure the length of an arc of parallel in latitude 52° and to test the accuracy of the figure and dimensions of the Earth, as derived from the measurements of <b>arc</b> <b>of</b> <b>meridian.</b> In order to combine the measurements it was necessary to compare the geodetic standards of length used in the different countries. The British Government invited those of France, Belgium, Prussia, Russia, India, Australia, Austria, Spain, United States and Cape of Good Hope to send their standards to the Ordnance Survey office in Southampton. Notably the standards of France, Spain and United States where based on the metric system, whereas those of Prussia, Belgium and Russia where calibrated against the toise which the oldest physical representative was the Toise of Peru. The Toise of Peru had been constucted in 1735 for Bouguer and Lacondamine as their standard of reference in the operation conducted in actual Ecuador from 1735 to 1744 in collaboration with the Spanish officers Jorge Juan and Antonio de Ulloa.|$|E
